<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/1306844-melissa"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1215477526i/1306844._UY100_CR24,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/1306844-melissa">Melissa</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Morton's ending of this overblown novel is very weak, messily put together and nonsensical. There is absolutely no mention of Lucy getting a bump on t<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Morton's ending of this overblown novel is very weak, messily put together and nonsensical. There is absolutely no mention of Lucy getting a bump on the head - no where - but she suddenly has one which conveniently renders her unable to share with her brother what actually happened. She apparently does figure it out fairly soon thereafter, yet contrary to her worshipful relationship with him, she never tells him the truth. I just don't buy it. The amnesia is a cheap trick, it seems to be added almost as an afterthought - and the resulting actions do not square with the character at all. I really expected better of Morton than this. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
